You're referring to this from the earlier example:

```java
ExecutorService executor = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(4);

CompletableFuture<Integer> future = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> {
    return 42;
}, executor);

executor.shutdown();
```

---

**The problem here** — `executor.shutdown()` is called immediately after submitting the task, before it even finishes. This works *by chance* because `shutdown()` doesn't kill running tasks, it just stops accepting new ones.

But it's misleading and risky. Better pattern:

```java
ExecutorService executor = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(4);

CompletableFuture<Integer> future = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> {
    return 42;
}, executor);

future.thenAccept(result -> System.out.println("Result: " + result))
      .whenComplete((v, ex) -> executor.shutdown()); // shutdown AFTER task is done
```

---

**Why use a custom Executor at all?**

By default `supplyAsync()` uses `ForkJoinPool.commonPool()` which is shared across your entire application.

| | `ForkJoinPool` (default) | Custom Executor |
|---|---|---|
| Shared across app | ✅ Yes | ❌ No, isolated |
| Good for CPU tasks | ✅ Yes | ⚠️ Depends |
| Good for blocking I/O (API calls) | ❌ No | ✅ Yes |
| Control over thread count | ❌ No | ✅ Yes |

**Your API call scenario is a perfect case for a custom executor** — because API calls are blocking I/O, and tying up the common pool threads with blocking calls starves the rest of your app.

```java
// Dedicated thread pool for API calls
ExecutorService apiExecutor = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(10);

CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> apiClient.fetchRecord(), apiExecutor)
    .thenApply(record -> transformer.toLocalDto(record))
    .thenApply(dto -> repository.save(dto))
    .thenApply(saved -> apiClient.acknowledge(saved.getId()))
    .whenComplete((v, ex) -> apiExecutor.shutdown());
```

This keeps your API threads isolated and your common pool free for CPU work.
